Anonymous Fri 28 Apr 2023 14:21:58 No.56097478 Report

>The Kash'gons Chronicles By Wizdoggo
https://rentry.org/oebpx

>017: Journey to the Desert (3/3)

I opened my eyes and found myself in a strange place, surrounded by unfamiliar faces. The heat had taken its toll on me, and I felt a headache pounding in my temples. I tried to sit up but felt dizzy and collapsed back onto the sand.

A group of cat-like people stood around me, their eyes curious yet cautious. Some were tall and slender with large ears, while others were shorter and stockier with stripes and spots on their fur. They spoke in a dialect of Kash'gonian that I couldn't understand, and I struggled to communicate with them.

I managed to convey that I was here to learn about their culture, and I told them about my travels and experiences with the Kash'gon. They seemed intrigued by my stories, and after some discussion, a tall Serval woman named Razina offered to be my guide.

She was stoic and calm, and as tall as Riama. She wore a long robe made of light fabric that fluttered in the breeze, and her piercing green eyes studied me intently. I felt a bit intimidated by her height and presence, but I also sensed that she was trustworthy.

Razina led me through the dunes, pointing out various plants and animals and telling me their uses in their culture. We stopped to rest in the shade of a rocky outcropping, and she showed me how to build a simple shelter using sand and sticks.

As we walked, I couldn't help but notice the differences between these desert people and the Kash'gon I had met before. Their lifestyle was harsh and unforgiving, yet they seemed to have a deep respect for the land and a connection to nature that was unlike anything I had seen before.

Despite the challenges of the desert, I felt a sense of excitement and curiosity stirring within me. I was eager to continue my journey and see where it would lead me next.

Thank you for your observation. You make a good point.
>the viewpoint character's internal dialogue is awfully observant, and awfully talk-y, for someone who apparently just almost died of heatstroke.
While it is true that John's internal dialogue may seem observant and talkative for someone who just experienced heatstroke, it's important to consider that people react differently to such situations. Some may become delirious or incoherent, while others may become more introspective and reflective. Additionally, John may have taken some time to recover before engaging in conversation with the desert people.
additionally being a traveler and someone who wants to learn about other cultures made him write everything in his journal (yes those entries are in his journal)

> How has he come to the conclusion that "their lifestyle was harsh and unforgiving?"
Regarding his observation on the harshness of their lifestyle, it's possible that John was able to infer this from their appearance and the nature of the environment they lived in. He saw that they were thin and lean, likely due to a lack of resources in the harsh desert environment. He also saw that they were wearing loose and breathable clothing, likely to protect themselves from the scorching sun. These observations could have led him to believe that their lifestyle was indeed harsh and unforgiving.

Anonymous Fri 28 Apr 2023 15:02:08 No.56097931 Report
Quoted By:
>>56097768
>While it is true that John's internal dialogue may seem observant and talkative for someone who just experienced heatstroke, it's important to consider that people react differently to such situations.
Wrong perspective.
Let me reveal some words you forgot to type here.
>I think that it's important for my readers to consider…
As the author, your role is to present ideas that invite the reader to think. It is not to require the reader to think about special cases that would justify your narrative designs. The reader is reading for pleasure, not for the chore of accepting that you're writing a character who behaves as an unusual but plausible case. Spend suspension of disbelief on cool premise, not on characters behaving in ways that are difficult for the reader to empathize with.

>Some may become delirious or incoherent, while others may…
True. And to use this fact, you need two or more characters to portray those possibilities. With one character, either you've already established how he handles that kind of stress, or go with what the reader will find believable unless his odd reaction is crucial to the next plot development.

>John may have taken some time to recover
>it's possible that John was able
>These observations could have
May? Possible? Could? You don't know? You're the author. Either he did or he didn't, and either you portrayed it in the story or hid it for a specific narrative purpose. Reader isn't here to guess at decisions you haven't made. Indeed, instead of making a decision, you've made an EXCUSE.

You could have him recovering, observing, working out things, and coming to a conclusion. Instead you throw a dart and want the reader to justify where it landed.

That's weak and sloppy. And by not knowing for yourself, you have no foundation for building interesting revelations.

Now, let's punch this up.

A headache pounded between my temples and when I opened my eyes I saw only blurs. I tried to sit up. The blurs were faced, unfamiliar and cat-like, with eyes curious yet cautious. Dizziness overwhelmed me before I could make anything more of what I saw, and I collapsed back onto the sand. They began speaking syllables that inflamed my headache and rang with the texture of Kash'gonian. Their dialect was alien to me, and the dialect I could offer was as confounding to them. But I had nothing else, so I babbled about my cause, to learn of their culture, and that I had already lived among Kash'gon.

There were at least two bloodlines, as some were tall and slender and others short, stocky, with stripes and spots. They came and went and brought others. I thought maybe I was a spectacle till one of the tall kind sat beside me. She had visited me not long ago and left quickly. Now she brought something like a thin soup and asked me to drink it with words I understood. For about five minutes we sat in silence, her piercing green eyes studying me while my eyes watched her long robe flutter in the breeze. Then, as though she had finished counting down the seconds, she grasped me and stood, pulling me onto my feet. Even on the soft sand, I felt more sure and steady than I had since the heat had first gotten to me. Even upright, she was tall, and carried an intimidating presence, but not threatening; she felt trustworthy, like a benevolent regent.

She led me through the dunes, and started a conversation. Simple things at first, she gave me her name, Razina, and asked for mine. She pointed out medicinal plants and animals important to their lifestyle. And when we came upon a shaded outcropping of stone, she demonstrated how they construct simple shelters.

These Kash'gon lived differently from their cousins I'd met before. Their land was harsh and unforgiving of disrespect. Survival there required understanding of those who survived before you, as part of the ecosystem, not as a conqueror of it. Razina made clear to me, if not in the most clear of words, that I was welcome to dwell among them and in the desert beyond, but only if I learned their ways would I be able to dwell for long.

A sense of curiosity stirred within me, an excitement to face the desert's challenge. I felt eager to continue my journey, but also slightly reluctant. As Razina led me back to her people's encampment, another feeling sirred within me, one that wasn't eager to leave; to leave her side, to be precise.

There were creatures like that--not sapient, just animals--in a Larry Niven novel written in the 1970s. It isn't one of his better works, but it involves traveling long distances through space at just under the speed of light. The protagonist takes such a journey and returns to Earth, seemingly several million years after he left. In a forest he sees predatory fuzzy cat-headed snake creatures. As they could not possibly have evolved naturally, he stares at them and wonders whether their were genetically engineered as pets, some time in the far-distant past, and left to fend for themselves after humans left, or went extinct, or whatever. I believe the author said later that he was inspired by outlandish cat-headed snake plushies he saw offered as prizes at a carnival.
